#ask
Good evening.
I have a question about one of Scrum artifacts, which is Increments.

In what format usually an increment represented?
I'm currently building a web service using Scrum, and I confuse how to represent the increments of a sprint. 

Thanks in advance.

(1 + 6) [@IRAQIA6k](tg://user?id=1112225104), please, send the solution to the arithmetic operation provided within the time amount specified to this group, otherwise you will be kicked. Thank you! (60 sec)\nPowered by [Todorant](https://todorant.com/?ref=shieldy)
Product Increment - this is difference between the product from the previous sprint to the product you produce and release this sprint.
at the code level, it's the code diff between the older version and the new build - code added, deleted, modified.
for the business, its more meaningful to  describe the product increment as features added, modified, deleted, plus bugs fixed
If you are doing scrum, you should have sprint goals and your product increment should reflect those sprint goals
bear in mind the product increment is the product itself, not a document describing the product increment

Thanks for the explanation, Sir. I've read several resources about how to represent the Product Increment.

It's pretty much just like the Product Backlog Item without estimation time.

If I cite your statement, then how could I represent the Product Increment in my project report, Sir?

its the increment of the product for each sprint.   In a project report you would say in sprint X the product increment includes feature A, B, C and bugs fixed X, Y.   Level of detail is up to you.   I would not predict product increment too far ahead of each sprint as this will change frequently.
Thankyou Sir. So helpful

Good afternoon. I have a question.
I'm currently writing a project report that uses Scrum as the framework. I'm wondering how should I report all the steps we've been through in Scrum, like sprint review and sprint retrospective.
Are those steps need to be documented?

If yes, in what format should I make the sprint review and sprint retrospective.
If no, why? And how can I prove that as I'm doing the project, all the mandatory steps in Scrum were done by the team?
oh my, saying "oh my g**" is not allowed by the bot? that's gotta be an overzealous filter if I ever saw one

anyway, this is anecdotal, but I found the strongest PMs/POs that I historically worked with have either a bachelor in tech and master in business, or have worked a lot in business ops for a large-scale tech company
the latter is important because it gave them very strong customer-centric empathy and perspective, which I consider as critical for any good POs

I will make it simple if i have to make some report..

From this x sprint, 
- what is our sprint goal 
- what is our PBI, 
- how many done --> show & demo it
- how many not done --> why.
Reporting scrum event doesn't add value, the only mathers are working software & point of improvement

Sprint plan - record the sprint goals determined and which work/stories are to be executed during the sprint.   
Sprint review - what stories/work was completed and demo-d to stakeholders
Sprint retro - usually this is kept private within the team but you could record what actions were planned out of the retro.
This is a fairly lightweight way of demonstrating that your team "followed" scrum, if you have to show that
And Angga is right, its essentially waste to record this and write it into a project report but sometimes organisations demand this üòä

Q: what do you think about Enterprise Agile Framework? What is EAF?
I would like to start a discussion
Since there's a trending out there
What is it? üòÑ
that is part of the question
since recently I see a lot asking about it
do we use/want to use Enterprise Agile Framework
some relate it with Scaled Agile Framework

In my opinion EAF mostly a biggest model of Scrum üòÅ, for example Less, Safe, DaD.. they comes by needed frim enterprise to adopting Agile. thats good, but I still believe even we are a huge company better to start from small..  üòÅ
yes agree on that but you know consultants sometime want to show something fancy, complex so they can offer services
For sure it's a good topic pak.. since many enterprise look into Agile now.. eager to learn on this discussion...

Yes... that's what i mean to start small even you are enterprise, to have an experience and grow by condition. and I agree there is consultant out there abuse the concept.. offer the shortcut which is not really short..
Being Agile is about a journey, you need to do, feel, and getting experience by yourself.. and you will know what you need to grow.. empirism :)

If it's a prescriptive model similar to safe, I'd argue we don't need it. All big enterprises I've worked with so far, have a different context. Imposing one model or structure doesn't work and creates confusion.

Especially agile on a wider enterprise scale. There are many functions, products and services, processes to deliver those. Bringing that all together in an agile way, means we need to co create the structure and culture, based on the conditions and iteratively evolve the 'system'

I think what's also important is that the company top leaderships know what is the vision  of their agile transformation. What value are they trying to get and not for the sake of implementing something "agile".  \n\nA lot of consultants made a mistake trying to drop in a pre-defined model without understanding the culture of the company. The most interesting part is the culture shift and that requires clear vision from the company leadership.

Transformation that is normally top down driven has a bigger chance to success

Berikut obrolan Rizky & Mufid di sesi klinik sebelumnya. Kita membahas prasyarat utama sebelum implementasi Scrum.

Kesimpulannya ada dua poin:

1. Pihak stakeholder/management/owner perlu tahu bedanya mindset agile & mindset proyek (waterfall) ‚Äî> caranya lewat teknik2 edukasi yang baik. 

2. Pihak developer perlu punya mindset untuk selalu deliver value ke user (bukan hanya memenuhi janji/kontrak) ‚Äî> caranya bisa dengan memperbanyak & mempersering momen selebrasi, ketika mereka berhasil membuat real user (pengguna profuk) lebih bahagia.

di sesi ngobrol2 Klinik Gratis minggu lalu, kita coba jawab pertanyaan berikut :

‚ÄúBagaimana Cara Membangun Tim Developer yang Profesional?‚Äù

__Kenapa pertanyaan ini penting?__ Karena Scrum Guide jelas2 meminta Tim Scrum  level profesional. __Kenapa ga boleh amatir?__ Menurut saya, karena kekerenan Scrum dalam melatih akurasi estimasi developer bisa berkurang drastis ‚Äî selain untuk mengoptimalkan delivery value ke user tentunya.

Berikut jawaban Mufid, seorang praktisi & konsultan __software engineering__:

‚ÄúUntuk membangun tim developer yang profesional, pertama, petakan dulu tipe inisiatif kamu: RnD atau Produk.

Kalau tipe RnD, maka checklist2 teknis harus dipenuhi oleh developer yang akan kamu rekrut.. 

Kalau tipe Produk, menenuhi checklist2 teknis akan membantu.. cuma‚Ä¶
